                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d445">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 1229/1.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Higgins</persName>
                    </hi> (<hi rend="italic">for the British Ambassador</hi>) <hi rend="italic">to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Lenox, Mass.</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1906-10-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 10, 1906</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 195.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I had the honor to communicate to His Majesty’s
                    secretary of state for foreign affairs the fact that the United States
                    Government were willing to forego provisionally their extraterritorial rights in
                    Zanzibar, which you notified to me in your note No. 489 of July 27.</p>
                <p>I am now instructed by Sir Edward Grey to express to you the thanks of His
                    Majesty’s Government for the courteous manner in which their desires on the
                    subject have been met.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cecil Higgins</hi>,</signed>
                    <lb/>(For the Ambassador.)</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
